# TODO

- Milestone focus (near-term)
  - Parser-rewrite milestone path: prioritize runtime and language completeness over advanced analysis.
  - Complete integer division in runtime (`Integer¸divide` full multi-digit divisor support).
  - Keep subset constraints enforcing compile-time assignment compatibility.
  - Defer advanced lattice/control-flow narrowing until more core types exist (`data`/`object`/`service`/`enum`/`union`).

- Lattices and narrowing (deferred until more types exist)
  - Replace family-only types with value-sets across semantic flow states.
  - Keep current subset checks and string constraints as the baseline (already useful without full path analysis).
  - Future static code-path analysis and narrowing by control flow/path conditions.
  - Future optimization hook: fold pure expressions when analysis proves a single possible value.

- Control-flow narrowing V1 (after integer division; truthvalue-first)
  - Start with branch-local truthvalue narrowing in `if`/`else`.
  - Extend to subset-aware assignment checks inside guarded branches (e.g. `if (x < 5) { y = x }`).
  - Join branch states conservatively at merge points.
  - Add diagnostics for impossible branches/contradictory predicates only where semantics are already precise.
- `data`, `object` and `service` types
  - Heap allocated and reference counted
  - `data` is a naked data structure — no methods
  - `object` is encapsulated data — only accessed through methods
  - `service` is like `object` but not restricted to its own heap memory
  - `enum` list of values (like `truthvalue`)
  - tagged `union` types (labelled data structures, no tuples)
    - `x.casename?.property`
- Validation: `service` type cannot be assigned to `const`/`mut` variables
- `trait` applicable to data-oriented type (i.e. `data` and `object`)
- `role` applicable to `service` (`ref` only)
- Control flow
  - Ternary operator with Python syntax: `a if x else b if !x else c`
  - `unless (predicate) { return/continue/break }` (guard clause)
  - `if const cn = nullable { /* cn is available (and not null) inside the block */ }`
  - `unless const cn = x.casename { return } // cn exists (and is not null) after block`
  - `for in` (no C-like `for` loop)
  - `when`, `=>` pattern matching
  - `when` as expression
  - `while` and (maybe) `until`

## To be considered after deferred lattice/narrowing is resumed

- Referential constraints such as `func add(a: integer, b: integer) -> integer @value(a+b)`
- Staggered lattices `integer @range(1...10) \/ @range(55...100)` (where `\/` means union or join)
- Optimise/prune the AST based on known value-sets

